Well, I'm flying this plane today.
First complaint: We need cute flight logbooks. Black is too boring, and pink isn't even pink—it's actually salmon red.
I've always wanted to fly.
Today, my dream has come true... I flew a plane today. I'm still in shock.
FlightAware's data.
I plan to try again this Saturday. The weather doesn't look good now, but today is only Monday.
It seems the challenges in this area are beginning to show. Due to the FAA's stance on certain medications, I may have difficulty obtaining a medical certificate.
This is not impossible, but it will require a lot of time and a great deal of extra work.
Although this is a bit discouraging, it's just another problem that needs to be solved, and it seems "definitely" solvable at the moment. It just requires a lot of time and money.
If you want to know what challenges I will face next:
The FAA doesn't like ADHD. If you're taking medication for ADHD, you definitely won't get a medical certificate.
https://youtu.be/W5JSfq6LLAU?si=xIxPaY8ayqqNSj4c
If I ever have the opportunity to customize an airplane's tail number, it has to be some variation of N1337_, where _ represents any available letter character.
Of course, the sun will definitely rise as usual while I'm gone, haha. That's really spoiling the fun.
I have to fly again. But this lousy weather is really not cooperating.
Welcome to the world of general aviation! 😜
Based on the YouTube ads I should be seeing, the videos recommended to me, and the comments, I feel that airlines tend to be conservative in their tracking.
If the weather allows, I'll fly again on Saturday.
Additionally, I found a pink flight logbook.
Good morning Saturday. I did this today ^_^
#TeaganAir
The flight logbook is officially in use now. I have 2.3 hours of flight time recorded ^_^
#TeaganAir
If you let me describe what it feels like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like driving a combination of a motorcycle, all-terrain vehicle, and a boat at 4000 feet in the air.
On the ground, conditions change rapidly. There is a certain level of instability, hence the need for a motorcycle/all-terrain vehicle.
Also, you might not know that when driving an airplane on the ground, you use your feet to control direction, not the control yoke. It uses rudder pedals and brakes. It's not a car.
When flying in the air, you'll experience turbulence and shaking, feeling much like sailing on water in a boat. Although you can control the airplane, sometimes the air currents can make you a bit disoriented, so you need to adapt to flying in the air just as a sailor adapts to sailing.
By the way, there's also a random little anecdote:
Flying is very physically demanding. My back and legs are aching badly today, feeling like I've been to the gym.
This isn't as simple as going for a drive on Sunday. From my novice perspective, it's more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, happy Saturday. Welcome to 4000 feet in the air.
I will fly again tomorrow, and we will practice stalls and slow flight.
Today's weather wasn't very stable, but it was super interesting. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed once dropped to 16 miles per hour, while our airspeed was still at 65 miles per hour.
Today's weather is clear, though the high altitude is a bit foggy, the view is still great.
